<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROUNDUP; SANTA CLARA STREAK GOES TO 83 GAMES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Damien Cantrell scored 34 points and Jess Pena added 17 as Santa Clara High 
defeated Calabasas, 74-51, in a Frontier League basketball game Tuesday night 
at Calabasas. 
</P>
<P>
 It was the Saints' 83rd consecutive league victory, the second-longest streak 
in Southern Section history. Banning won 98 league games in a row from 1983-91. 
</P>
<P>
 Santa Clara (15-7, 7-0 in league play), which has won 12 Southern Section 
titles during Coach Lou Cvijanovich's 36 years at the school, won 82 
consecutive league games from 1956-65. 
</P>
<P>
 The Saints' victory overshadowed a 31-point, 12-rebound performance by 
sophomore Nick Alexander of Calabasas (10-12, 1-6). 
</P>
<P>
 Palmdale 77, Ridgecrest Burroughs 73 -- Mike Hamelin had 17 points and 12 
rebounds at Palmdale as the Falcons (20-3, 14-0) gave Garry Phelps his first 
20-win season in 15 years as coach. Demario Brown scored 30 points for the 
Burros. 
</P>
<P>
 Glendale 79, Arcadia 52 -- Manny Gonzalez scored 20 points and the Dynamiters 
remained tied with Muir for the Pacific League lead with one game left. 
</P>
<P>
 St. Francis 58, St. Paul 48 -- The Golden Knights (19-5, 10-1) remained 
one-half game ahead of St. John Bosco in the Del Rey League. Dan Bir had 20 
points and Chris Ott added 16 for St. Francis. 
</P>
<P>
 Burbank 38, Saugus 37 -- Brad Warner, who had 13 points and 11 rebounds, gave 
the Bulldogs a victory with a basket at the buzzer. Warner also hit a jump shot 
with 31 seconds left and got assists from Jason Jonas on both baskets. 
</P>
<P>
 Muir 60, Hoover 48 -- Eric Walker scored 16 points and Artin Avenessian added 
14, but they couldn't prevent Hoover (8-15, 1-8) from falling in a Pacific 
League game. 
</P>
<P>
 Crescenta Valley 68, Pasadena 61 -- Richard O'Neill scored 25 points to lead 
the Falcons (15-8, 5-4) to a Pacific League victory at Pasadena. 
</P>
<P>
 Bravo Medical 99, Valley Alternative 47 -- Despite Mike Lyubarsky's 12 points, 
Valley Alternative (1-12) lost in the first round of the Magnet League 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
 Harvard-Westlake 73, Alemany 54 -- Scott Garson and Ben Robbins led the 
Wolverines (20-2, 10-2) to their first 20-victory season since 1990. Garson had 
17 points and six assists, and Robbins had 10 points and seven assists. GIRLS' 
BASKETBALL 
</P>
<P>
 Newbury Park 39, Channel Islands 37 -- Julie Wastell made a 15-foot jump shot 
with eight seconds to play and stole the ball with two seconds left as the 
Panthers handed Channel Islands (20-3, 12-1) its first Marmonte League defeat. 
</P>
<P>
 Wastell led Newbury Park (12-4, 11-2) with 13 rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
 Village Christian 81, L.A. Baptist 51 -- The Crusaders (21-1, 8-0) capped 
their second consecutive undefeated season in the Alpha League by scoring a 
school-record 39 points in the third quarter and equaled their record for most 
victories in a season. 
</P>
<P>
 Simi Valley 57, Westlake 41 -- Sara Griffin had 23 points, six rebounds and 
five assists for the Pioneers (15-11, 7-6). WOMEN'S BASKETBALL 
</P>
<P>
 Cal Lutheran 77, Redlands 62 -- Melissa Wood made six three-pointers and 
scored 25 points but the Regals (6-11, 2-6) were dominated in a SCIAC game at 
Thousand Oaks. BOYS' SOCCER 
</P>
<P>
 Moorpark 6, Santa Paula 0 -- Curtis Silverest scored three goals and Pat Russo 
added two as the Musketeers (22-2, 7-0) clinched their second consecutive 
Fronter League championship. 
