</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO FOCUS: LOS ANGELES; RIORDAN URGES SCRAPPING LITTLE TOKYO OFFICE PROJECT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Mayor Richard Riordan recommended Tuesday that the city scuttle a 6-year-old 
proposal to build a municipal office building in conjunction with a private 
hotel, apartment and retail development near Little Tokyo in Downtown Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 In a letter to the City Council, Riordan called the $151-million office tower 
too expensive. He added that the plan does not coincide with guidelines to 
bolster development in the downtrodden historic core of the city and also 
provides too much space for a city work force that has been shrinking steadily. 
</P>
<P>
 A Los Angeles City Council committee voted Tuesday evening to give the 
so-called First Street North project, proposed for Alameda and 1st streets, 
more study. 
</P>
</TEXT>
