<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO FOCUS: PASADENA; COUNCIL ACCEPTS $140,000 IN SUPER BOWL TICKET DISPUTE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Pasadena City Council voted Tuesday night to accept at least $140,000 from 
the nonprofit Los Angeles Sports Council to settle its dispute over a revenue 
shortfall associated with the sale of 700 tickets to Super Bowl XXVII. 
</P>
<P>
 The 700 tickets were among 2,500 tickets that were to be sold at premium 
prices in hospitality packages, generating $1 million for city coffers.City 
officials planned to use the money to help pay for a new $11.5-million press 
box they had built at the Rose Bowl to accommodate last year's game. 
</P>
<P>
 But packages containing the 700 tickets remained unsold several days before 
the game, said officials of the Sports Council, the coordinating group for 
Super Bowl XXVII. So the tickets were sold at face value, creating a shortfall 
of about $800,000. 
</P>
<P>
 City officials initially demanded that the Sports Council disclose who bought 
the coveted tickets at face value but dropped the issue Tuesday after receiving 
assurances that nothing had been remiss in the way the tickets were sold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
