MASS. GOVERNOR SEEKS DEATH PENALTY RENEWAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Gov. William F. Weld on Tuesday called for reinstatement of the death penalty 
after two police officers in the state were shot and killed within a week. Weld 
refiled a broad package of anti-crime legislation, first proposed in 1991, 
calling for restoration of the death sentence and mandatory life sentences for 
repeat felons convicted of violent crimes. 
</P>
